Results and discussion
Present polymers of bpz ligand involving typical octahedral metal centers (Zn2+, Cd2+, Cu2+, Co2+) are classified by the dimensionality of coordination network. It is necessary to note two important distinctions between typical linear rod-like connector such as bipy and bpz. Firstly, even if bpz is planar and trans-configured, a perpendicular shift between almost co-directed NM bonds takes place (
). An important special case of linear coordination is demonstrated to show how such successive shifts can be additive, or to compensate each other, depending on orientation around coordination center. Thus the topologies based upon bpz actually can adopt certain flexibility; arrays involving co-directed bonds such as 1D chains or 2D square grids nets can undulate providing zig–zag chains or corrugated 2D layers. Secondly, the close disposition of NH group to coordination binding site can affect on coordination via H-bonding with participation of coordinated counter anion. This succeeds in a certain specific orientation of the tectons around the metal center. Besides, inclusion of H-acceptors via bonding with the same group apparently can be anticipated.

2D coordination nets
Coordination linkage of all characterized complexes possessing 2D layered structure exists as ‘square grids’ (4,4) nets {M(bpz)2}∞ (Shläfly topology symbol 4462
) with somewhat different metrics (
). Metal centers have slightly distorted octahedral environment with closer four N atoms of bpz and more distant atoms of chloride or oxygen atoms of counter anions or water molecules. Degree of such axial distortion is maximal in case of copper complex, and appreciable in chloride complexes. In two of six structures (4 and 7) the pyrazole cycles of the ligand are not coplanar. Last fact shows that similarly to 4,4′-bipyridine the bpz tecton is not absolutely rigid, but affirms the planar geometry as most characteristic.
